      "question": "If the prime factorization of a positive integer $n$ is given by $n = 2^3 \times 3^2 \times p$ and the prime factorization of $m$ is $2^2 \times 3 \times q$, where $p$ and $q$ are distinct prime numbers other than $2$ and $3$, then the HCF of $n$ and $m$ is:",
      "answer": "(A)",
      "solution": {
        "steps": [
          "Identify the prime factorization of $n$ as $2^3 \times 3^2 \times p$.",
          "Identify the prime factorization of $m$ as $2^2 \times 3^1 \times q$.",
          "The HCF of two numbers is the product of the smallest powers of each common prime factor.",
          "The common prime factors are $2$ and $3$.",
          "The smallest power of $2$ is $2^2$ and the smallest power of $3$ is $3^1$.",
          "Calculate $HCF = 2^2 \times 3^1 = 4 \times 3 = 12$."
        ],
        "derivation": "$n = 2^3 \times 3^2 \times p \\\\ m = 2^2 \times 3^1 \times q \\\\ HCF(n, m) = 2^{\\min(3, 2)} \times 3^{\\min(2, 1)} \\\\ HCF(n, m) = 2^2 \times 3^1 \\\\ HCF(n, m) = 4 \times 3 = 12$"
      },
      "topic": "Real Numbers",
      "subtopic": "Fundamental Theorem of Arithmetic (HCF)",
